04267nam a22006495i 9780271033105DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20212007pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710331057 a10.1515/97802710331052doi  a(DE-B1597)584163  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJN6699.A15bC38 2007eb 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a306.209472221 aCarnaghan, Ellen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOut of Order :bRussian Political Values in an Imperfect World /cEllen Carnaghan. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Transliteration -- t1 Out of Order -- t2 The Tangled Web of Culture -- t3 Russians in Their Own Words -- t4 Abstract Notions of Democracy Versus Current Experiences -- t5 Views of Markets: Russians Confront Inequality -- t6 Views on Order, Disorder, and Democracy -- t7 Views of Change: The More Things Change, the More They Stay the Same -- t8 What Russians Want -- t9 Conclusion -- tAppendixes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne common explanation for the failure of democracy to take root in Russia more quickly and more thoroughly than it has points to inherited cultural values that predispose Russian citizens to favor an autocratic type of governance. Ellen Carnaghan takes aim at this cultural-determinist thesis in her study of Russian attitudes, based on intensive interviews with more than sixty citizens from all walks of life and a variety of political orientations. What she finds is that, rather than being influenced by an antidemocratic and anticapitalist ideology, these ordinary citizens view the economic and political system in Russia today very critically because it simply does not function well for them in meeting their everyday needs. They long for order not because they eschew democracy and free markets in any fundamental way, but because they experience them currently as chaotic and unpredictable, leading to constant frustration. As a result, there is reason to be optimistic about further progress in democratization: it depends on improving the functioning of existing institutions, not transforming deep-rooted cultural norms. In the Conclusion, Carnaghan applies her argument to elucidating the reasons why Russians have responded favorably to what Westerners see as moves in an antidemocratic direction by Vladimir Putin's government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aPolitical culturezRussia (Federation). 0aPublic opinionzRussia (Federation). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271033105zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271033105423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271033105.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK